,"Sauchie, Clackmannan, Scotland":"Sauchie, Clackmannanshire, Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"–ABT 1530":"–about 1530","–1530":"–1530","1500–1547":"1500–1547","       1500":"1500","1547":"1547","1500":"1500","ABT 1530":"about 1530","1530":"1530","of Finderlie and Balquharn, Kincardine, Scotland":"Kincardineshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","Sauchie, Clackmannan, Scotland":"Sauchie, Clackmannanshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Shaw","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Yorkshire and Lancashire): from Middle English <i>s(c)hawe</i>, <i>s(c)haghe</i> ‘small wood, grove, thicket’ (Old English <i>sceaga</i>). The surname may be topographic, for someone who lived in or by a small wood, or habitational, for someone from any of the many places so named. <i>Shaw</i> and <i>Shawe</i> are most frequent in Lancashire and Yorkshire, where Shaw in Oldham (Lancashire) may be a principal source of the surname. The English and Lowland Scottish surname was also established in Ireland in the 17th century.","Scottish: shortened form of various surnames from the Gaelic personal name <i>Sitheach</i>, derived from <i>sithech</i> ‘wolf’.","Irish (Down and Antrim): adopted for <b>Ó Síthigh</b> ‘descendant of <i>Sítheach</i>’, a personal name based on <i>sítheach</i> ‘peaceful’. Compare   Sheehy  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Show","meanings":["English (Lancashire and Cumberland): probably a variant of   Shaw  , perhaps representing a blend in Middle English of Old English <i>sceaga</i> and Old Norse <i>skógr</i>, both meaning ‘wood’.","Perhaps an Americanized form of German   Schau  ."]},{"name":"Sheehy","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Aileen, Aisling, Brigid, Declan, Egan, Eoin, Finbar, Ronan.","Irish (Limerick and Kerry): shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Síthigh</b>, ‘descendant of <i>Sítheach</i>’, or <b>Mac Síthigh</b> ‘son of <i>Sítheach</i>’, a form of the Irish personal name <i>Síodhach</i> ‘peaceful’, from the adjective <i>sítheach</i> ‘peaceful’ or ‘other worldly’ (see   Sheehan  ). The noun <i>síth</i>, from which this adjective derives, means basically ‘settlement’, hence both ‘peace’ and ‘place inhabited by other world beings’. This name was established in Ireland from the early 14th century, when a branch of the Scottish McDonnells, descended from <i>Sítheach</i>, great-grandson of Domhnaill, settled in the country."]}]},{"name":"Gelise","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["short form of   Elisabeth .  The name was introduced into the English-speaking world (where it is often written without the accent) in the late 19th century and has become fairly popularity in recent years."],"variants":[{"name":"Elisa","meanings":["short form of   Elisabeth .  The name was introduced into the English-speaking world (where it is often written without the accent) in the late 19th century and has become fairly popularity in recent years."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Gelise Shaw was born in Sauchie, Clackmannanshire, Scotland, United Kingdom. She married John Broun in 1500, in Sauchie, Clackmannanshire, Scotland, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died about 1530, in her hometown."},"et":{"–ABT 1530":"–umbes 1530","–1530":"–1530","1500–1547":"1500–1547","       1500":"1500","1547":"1547","1500":"1500","ABT 1530":"umbes 1530","1530":"1530","of Finderlie and Balquharn, Kincardine, Scotland":"Kincardineshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Sauchie, Clackmannan, Scotland":"Sauchie, Clackmannanshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"–ABT 1530":"–noin 1530","–1530":"–1530","1500–1547":"1500–1547","       1500":"1500","1547":"1547","1500":"1500","ABT 1530":"noin 1530","1530":"1530","of Finderlie and Balquharn, Kincardine, Scotland":"Kincardineshire, Skotlanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Sauchie, Clackmannan, Scotland":"Sauchie,